[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":743},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-18-comparison-operators\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-18-comparison-operators\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-18-comparison-operators\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-18-comparison-operators\u002F":720,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-18-comparison-operators\u002F":729},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190516\u002F803766782\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":703,"date":704,"description":705,"extension":706,"lang":707,"meta":708,"navigation":709,"path":710,"readingMinutes":80,"seo":711,"standalone":712,"stem":713,"tags":714,"tldr":717,"updated":704,"url":718,"__hash__":719},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-18-comparison-operators.md","[JS Weird World] No.18 Comparison Operators: Why Is 3 \u003C 2 \u003C 1 Actually true?","1000071274",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":697},"minimark",[11,16,20,65,82,85,111,118,125,131,142,163,168,177,198,216,237,242,252,259,262,286,301,322,325,346,355,358,376,379,395,401,408,418,433,442,447,462,468,471,480,483,488,505,516,519,535,541,586,592,596,613,651,657,666,672,682,686,693],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"comparison-operators","Comparison Operators",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Let's talk about comparison operators. The easiest way in is to just look at some code:",[21,22,27],"pre",{"className":23,"code":24,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","console.log(1 \u003C 2 \u003C 3);\n","js","",[28,29,30],"code",{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,32,35,39,43,46,50,54,57,59,62],"span",{"class":33,"line":34},"line",1,[31,36,38],{"class":37},"sMAXC","console.",[31,40,42],{"class":41},"sj_SG","log",[31,44,45],{"class":37},"(",[31,47,49],{"class":48},"sCcAr","1",[31,51,53],{"class":52},"sWyjQ"," \u003C",[31,55,56],{"class":48}," 2",[31,58,53],{"class":52},[31,60,61],{"class":48}," 3",[31,63,64],{"class":37},");\n",[17,66,67,68,71,72,74,75,74,78,81],{},"What do you think the answer is? ",[28,69,70],{},"true",", right? Makes sense — ",[28,73,49],{}," is less than ",[28,76,77],{},"2",[28,79,80],{},"3",". Correct.",[17,83,84],{},"But what about this one?",[21,86,88],{"className":23,"code":87,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"console.log(3 \u003C 2 \u003C 1);\n",[28,89,90],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,91,92,94,96,98,100,102,104,106,109],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,93,38],{"class":37},[31,95,42],{"class":41},[31,97,45],{"class":37},[31,99,80],{"class":48},[31,101,53],{"class":52},[31,103,56],{"class":48},[31,105,53],{"class":52},[31,107,108],{"class":48}," 1",[31,110,64],{"class":37},[17,112,113,114,117],{},"You'd expect ",[28,115,116],{},"false",", right? Let's check.",[17,119,120],{},[121,122],"img",{"alt":123,"src":124},"the answer","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fc4sVTmSh.png",[17,126,127,128,130],{},"WT... how is it ",[28,129,70],{},"? Try reading it out loud: \"3 less than 2 less than 1.\" Feels kind of right and kind of wrong at the same time. The reason comes down to operator precedence and associativity (I think calling it \"ordering\" is clearer, honestly). In this expression everyone has the same precedence — they're all the less-than operator — so we fall back to associativity to decide the order.",[17,132,133,134,137,138,141],{},"The ",[28,135,136],{},"\u003C"," operator is left-associative, so the left side runs first. What does ",[28,139,140],{},"3 \u003C 2"," give you?",[21,143,145],{"className":23,"code":144,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"console.log(3 \u003C 2);\n",[28,146,147],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,148,149,151,153,155,157,159,161],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,150,38],{"class":37},[31,152,42],{"class":41},[31,154,45],{"class":37},[31,156,80],{"class":48},[31,158,53],{"class":52},[31,160,56],{"class":48},[31,162,64],{"class":37},[17,164,165],{},[121,166],{"alt":116,"src":167},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FYNjWFjDh.png",[17,169,170,171,173,174,176],{},"So now what happens when we compare that ",[28,172,116],{}," against ",[28,175,49],{},"?",[21,178,180],{"className":23,"code":179,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"console.log(false \u003C 1);\n",[28,181,182],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,183,184,186,188,190,192,194,196],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,185,38],{"class":37},[31,187,42],{"class":41},[31,189,45],{"class":37},[31,191,116],{"class":48},[31,193,53],{"class":52},[31,195,108],{"class":48},[31,197,64],{"class":37},[17,199,200,201,205,206,208,209,211,212,215],{},"Here's where JavaScript's dynamic typing kicks in. It ",[202,203,204],"strong",{},"coerces"," the values in this comparison, and ",[28,207,116],{}," gets turned into a Number. And what does ",[28,210,116],{}," become as a number? ",[202,213,214],{},"0",".",[21,217,219],{"className":23,"code":218,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"console.log(0 \u003C 1);\n",[28,220,221],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,222,223,225,227,229,231,233,235],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,224,38],{"class":37},[31,226,42],{"class":41},[31,228,45],{"class":37},[31,230,214],{"class":48},[31,232,53],{"class":52},[31,234,108],{"class":48},[31,236,64],{"class":37},[17,238,239,240,215],{},"That's why it outputs ",[28,241,70],{},[243,244,245,249],"ul",{},[246,247,248],"li",{},"0 represents false",[246,250,251],{},"1 represents true",[17,253,254,255,258],{},"From a human's point of view, ",[28,256,257],{},"console.log(3 \u003C 2 \u003C 1);"," is flat-out wrong. But in JavaScript it's perfectly valid and correct.",[17,260,261],{},"So let's go back to the original example and break it down.",[21,263,264],{"className":23,"code":24,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},[28,265,266],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,267,268,270,272,274,276,278,280,282,284],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,269,38],{"class":37},[31,271,42],{"class":41},[31,273,45],{"class":37},[31,275,49],{"class":48},[31,277,53],{"class":52},[31,279,56],{"class":48},[31,281,53],{"class":52},[31,283,61],{"class":48},[31,285,64],{"class":37},[17,287,288,289,292,293,74,295,297,298,300],{},"We just said less-than is left-associative, so ",[28,290,291],{},"1 \u003C 2"," runs first. ",[28,294,49],{},[28,296,77],{},", so that's ",[28,299,70],{},", and now the program looks like this:",[21,302,304],{"className":23,"code":303,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"console.log(true \u003C 3);\n",[28,305,306],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,307,308,310,312,314,316,318,320],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,309,38],{"class":37},[31,311,42],{"class":41},[31,313,45],{"class":37},[31,315,70],{"class":48},[31,317,53],{"class":52},[31,319,61],{"class":48},[31,321,64],{"class":37},[17,323,324],{},"After JavaScript coerces it, the code becomes:",[21,326,328],{"className":23,"code":327,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"console.log(1 \u003C 3);\n",[28,329,330],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,331,332,334,336,338,340,342,344],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,333,38],{"class":37},[31,335,42],{"class":41},[31,337,45],{"class":37},[31,339,49],{"class":48},[31,341,53],{"class":52},[31,343,61],{"class":48},[31,345,64],{"class":37},[17,347,348,74,350,352,353,215],{},[28,349,49],{},[28,351,80],{},". Yep, so it's ",[28,354,70],{},[17,356,357],{},"Sometimes we want to use coercion on purpose — like turning a string number into an actual number, like this:",[21,359,361],{"className":23,"code":360,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"Number('1');\n",[28,362,363],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,364,365,368,370,374],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,366,367],{"class":41},"Number",[31,369,45],{"class":37},[31,371,373],{"class":372},"sTRMh","'1'",[31,375,64],{"class":37},[17,377,378],{},"But what if the string we're converting isn't a number?",[21,380,382],{"className":23,"code":381,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"Number('哈囉');\n",[28,383,384],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,385,386,388,390,393],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,387,367],{"class":41},[31,389,45],{"class":37},[31,391,392],{"class":372},"'哈囉'",[31,394,64],{"class":37},[17,396,397],{},[121,398],{"alt":399,"src":400},"not a number","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FSpeaR0wh.png",[17,402,403,404,407],{},"We get a special little thing back: ",[28,405,406],{},"NaN",", which stands for \"Not a Number.\"",[17,409,410,411,414,415,215],{},"The course also covers converting ",[28,412,413],{},"undefined"," and ",[28,416,417],{},"null",[21,419,421],{"className":23,"code":420,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"Number(undefined);\n",[28,422,423],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,424,425,427,429,431],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,426,367],{"class":41},[31,428,45],{"class":37},[31,430,413],{"class":48},[31,432,64],{"class":37},[17,434,435,436,438,439,441],{},"You just get ",[28,437,406],{}," (and from this we can tell that ",[28,440,413],{}," is actually a value — a special keyword).",[17,443,444,445,176],{},"What about ",[28,446,417],{},[21,448,450],{"className":23,"code":449,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"Number(null);\n",[28,451,452],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,453,454,456,458,460],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,455,367],{"class":41},[31,457,45],{"class":37},[31,459,417],{"class":48},[31,461,64],{"class":37},[17,463,464,465,467],{},"JavaScript defines ",[28,466,417],{}," as 0.",[17,469,470],{},"So the takeaway is that forced coercion is a dangerous thing — don't go reaching for it unless you actually need to.",[472,473,479],"iframe",{"height":474,"style":475,"scrolling":476,"title":477,"src":478,"frameBorder":476,"allowTransparency":70,"allowFullScreen":70},265,"width: 100%;","no","comparison operators","\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fembed\u002FYbLvrx\u002F?height=265&theme-id=0&default-tab=js,result","\n  See the Pen \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng\u002Fpen\u002FYbLvrx\u002F'>comparison operators\u003C\u002Fa> by HF\n  (\u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io\u002Fhsiangfeng'>@hsiangfeng\u003C\u002Fa>) on \u003Ca href='https:\u002F\u002Fcodepen.io'>CodePen\u003C\u002Fa>.\n",[12,481,482],{"id":26},"==",[17,484,485,487],{},[28,486,482],{}," is the double-equals operator. We can write something like this:",[21,489,491],{"className":23,"code":490,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"1 == 1;\n",[28,492,493],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,494,495,497,500,502],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,496,49],{"class":48},[31,498,499],{"class":52}," ==",[31,501,108],{"class":48},[31,503,504],{"class":37},";\n",[17,506,507,508,510,511,513,514,215],{},"You get ",[28,509,70],{},". This operator returns either ",[28,512,70],{}," or ",[28,515,116],{},[17,517,518],{},"But what about this?",[21,520,522],{"className":23,"code":521,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"1 == '1';\n",[28,523,524],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,525,526,528,530,533],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,527,49],{"class":48},[31,529,499],{"class":52},[31,531,532],{"class":372}," '1'",[31,534,504],{"class":37},[17,536,537,538,540],{},"You still get ",[28,539,70],{},". Why? Because JavaScript coerces both operands into the same type before comparing them. The problem is, that opens the door to some pretty weird stuff, like...",[21,542,544],{"className":23,"code":543,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"0 == false;\nvar a = false;\na == 0;\n",[28,545,546,557,573],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,547,548,550,552,555],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,549,214],{"class":48},[31,551,499],{"class":52},[31,553,554],{"class":48}," false",[31,556,504],{"class":37},[31,558,560,563,566,569,571],{"class":33,"line":559},2,[31,561,562],{"class":52},"var",[31,564,565],{"class":37}," a ",[31,567,568],{"class":52},"=",[31,570,554],{"class":48},[31,572,504],{"class":37},[31,574,576,579,581,584],{"class":33,"line":575},3,[31,577,578],{"class":37},"a ",[31,580,482],{"class":52},[31,582,583],{"class":48}," 0",[31,585,504],{"class":37},[17,587,588],{},[121,589],{"alt":590,"src":591},"double equals","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002F83eZ1Uxh.png",[12,593,595],{"id":594},"so-what-about","So what about ===?",[17,597,598,599,414,602,604,605,607,608,612],{},"The difference between ",[28,600,601],{},"===",[28,603,482],{}," is that ",[28,606,601],{}," doesn't do any coercion (you can also think of it as us ",[609,610,611],"em",{},"forbidding"," JavaScript from coercing for us). It compares using the current types directly.",[21,614,616],{"className":23,"code":615,"language":25,"meta":26,"style":26},"0 === false;\nvar a = false;\na === 0;\n",[28,617,618,629,641],{"__ignoreMap":26},[31,619,620,622,625,627],{"class":33,"line":34},[31,621,214],{"class":48},[31,623,624],{"class":52}," ===",[31,626,554],{"class":48},[31,628,504],{"class":37},[31,630,631,633,635,637,639],{"class":33,"line":559},[31,632,562],{"class":52},[31,634,565],{"class":37},[31,636,568],{"class":52},[31,638,554],{"class":48},[31,640,504],{"class":37},[31,642,643,645,647,649],{"class":33,"line":575},[31,644,578],{"class":37},[31,646,601],{"class":52},[31,648,583],{"class":48},[31,650,504],{"class":37},[17,652,653],{},[121,654],{"alt":655,"src":656},"triple equals","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002F0jqYsPQh.png",[17,658,659,660,662,663,665],{},"And that's exactly why, when writing JavaScript, we always recommend not using ",[28,661,482],{}," and using ",[28,664,601],{}," instead. It saves you from a whole pile of weird problems.",[17,667,668,669,671],{},"So what does ",[28,670,601],{}," mean? In short, it's strict mode — I don't want you (JavaScript) converting types, just compare using the current types as-is.",[17,673,674,675,215],{},"For more detail, check out this ",[676,677,681],"a",{"href":678,"rel":679},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FWeb\u002FJavaScript\u002FEquality_comparisons_and_sameness",[680],"nofollow","MDN doc",[12,683,685],{"id":684},"image-source","Image Source",[17,687,688],{},[676,689,692],{"href":690,"rel":691},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.udemy.com\u002Fjavascriptjs\u002F",[680],"JavaScript 全攻略:克服 JS 奇怪的部分",[694,695,696],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}",{"title":26,"searchDepth":559,"depth":559,"links":698},[699,700,701,702],{"id":14,"depth":559,"text":15},{"id":26,"depth":559,"text":482},{"id":594,"depth":559,"text":595},{"id":684,"depth":559,"text":685},"JsWeirdWorld","2019-05-16 21:16:35","Comparison operators look simple until you hit something like 3 \u003C 2 \u003C 1 and JavaScript hands you back true. In this post we walk through operator associativity, type coercion, NaN, and why == and === aren't the same thing — and why you should basically always reach for ===.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002Fjs-weird-world-18-comparison-operators",{"title":6,"description":705},false,"en\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-18-comparison-operators",[715,716],"JavaScript","JavaScript 全攻略:克服JS奇怪的部分",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-18-comparison-operators\u002F","BJsdpZ5RBj__Io-hv9OKZzDGWl2cQ4twbspLqndUeDk",{"newer":721,"older":725},{"url":722,"title":723,"date":724},"\u002Fen\u002Fhexo\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F17\u002Fhexo-url-optimization-seo\u002F","Hexo URL Optimisation (SEO)","2019-05-17 10:05:19",{"url":726,"title":727,"date":728},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-17-coercion\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.17 A Quick Reminder: Type Coercion","2019-05-16 21:01:35",[730,735,739],{"url":731,"title":732,"date":733,"readingMinutes":734},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F27\u002Fjs-weird-world-bonus-closures\u002F","[JS Weird World] Bonus: Closures, One More Time","2019-05-27 13:50:04","5",{"url":736,"title":737,"date":738,"readingMinutes":49},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-68-the-end-is-a-new-beginning\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.68 Wrapping Up the Weird Parts of JavaScript","2019-05-25 16:36:00",{"url":740,"title":741,"date":742,"readingMinutes":77},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-67-adding-jquery-support\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.67 Adding jQuery Support to Our Mini Framework","2019-05-25 16:19:00",1784010279206]